      <profileDesc>
         <abstract>
            <p>The synaxarion, Sǝnkǝsār in Ethiopia, is a liturgical work containing commemorative notices of persons, events or feasts for each day of the year. The Ethiopic
            Sǝnkǝsār war translated from the Copto-Arabic synaxarion at least twice (<ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4032SenkessarS"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: LIT4032SenkessarS</span></ref>
            and <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4033Senkessar"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: LIT4033Senkessar</span></ref>), each translation depending on a different Arabic Vorlage. The translation was extensively revised in Ethiopia, 
            both regarding content and language (<ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4968SenkessarSec"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: LIT4968SenkessarSec</span></ref>).</p>
         </abstract>
         <creation notBefore="1375" notAfter="1425" corresp="#Psttanthony">The translation  <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4032SenkessarS"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: LIT4032SenkessarS</span></ref> was carried out around
               <date>1400</date> by <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS8743Semon">Sǝmʿon</persName>, a monk of <placeName xml:id="Psttanthony" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0320DAA">Dayr ʾAnbā ʾAnṭūniyūs</placeName>, according to the colophon
            of the translation present in <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BNFabb66A"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: BNFabb66A</span></ref>.</creation>
         <creation notBefore="1375" notAfter="1400">The translation <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4033Senkessar"><span xmlns="" class="w3-tag w3-red">No item: LIT4033Senkessar</span></ref> goes probably also back to the end of the 14th
            century.</creation>
    
